					<div class="content-intro-text">
						<h1>Mundus maris progress report for February 2012</h1>
																								
													<p class="date"><strong>Date:</strong>
							08/03/2012</p>
																									<p class="intro">Introduction:</p>
							<p><b>Coordination</b></p><p>Among the major activities was the active participation of MM in several activities in the context of <b>Campus Plein Sud</b> (CPS) at the Free University of Brussels (ULB). We have scheduled the following together with SEDIF, which has the overall coordination of CPS:</p><p>The participation in the <b>NGO Forum</b> on 29/02 in a tent we happily shared with a campaign to vaccinate livestock in Africa was quite productive. We met with a number of interesting people and had good conversations about work of MM, in particular on how sciences and arts in support of protecting the sea can be shared more effectively by teachers and teacher trainers from different countries. Flyers were distributed widely and some visitors of our booth are now on the distribution list of this progress report. A special thanks to Cleo Zhang, who volunteered to help staff the booth.</p>
						
						
						
						<br/>&nbsp;
					</div> 
					<br class="cl">
				</div> 
				 
			
				<div id="content-item">
											<div class="box-content">
							<a class="storylist" href="/en/layout/set/print/content/view/full/14978">Print</a>
																				</div> 
						<br class="cl">
		
					 
	
				</div> 
			
				<div id="main-content" class="content view">					

	                          
			

	<!-- BEGIN BODY TEXT -->	
	
			<div class="stdtext">	
			
<p><b>Coordination</b></p><p>Among the major activities was the active participation of MM in several activities in the context of <b>Campus Plein Sud</b> (CPS) at the Free University of Brussels (ULB). We have scheduled the following together with SEDIF, which has the overall coordination of CPS:</p><p>The participation in the <b>NGO Forum</b> on 29/02 in a tent we happily shared with a campaign to vaccinate livestock in Africa was quite productive. We met with a number of interesting people and had good conversations about work of MM, in particular on how sciences and arts in support of protecting the sea can be shared more effectively by teachers and teacher trainers from different countries. Flyers were distributed widely and some visitors of our booth are now on the distribution list of this progress report. A special thanks to Cleo Zhang, who volunteered to help staff the booth.</p><p>The other contributions to CPS will be reported upon in the March report, but we are happy to anticipate that they all went very well. They are:</p>
<ul>

<li>our international <b>workshop ‘Learning, teaching and practicing sustainable development’</b>, 2-3 March 2012 in the Sociology Department, Solbosch Campus of the ULB: <a href="http://www.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/projects/2012projects-en/182-bxl-workshop-en" title="http://www.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/projects/2012projects-en/182-bxl-workshop-en" target="_blank">http://www.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/projects/2012projects-en/182-bxl-workshop-en</a></li>

<li><b>Cine-Debate</b> with the projection of the film ‘Kayar – l’enfance prise aux filets’ by Thomas Grand – in the course of Prof. Lancelot, Aliou Sall and Cornelia as discussants – others, of course, welcome – 5 March from 10-12h, Le Forum H - Campus de la Plaine</li>

<li><b>Open course</b> of Prof. Paul Jacobs – Cornelia will give a talk – 7 March from 16-18h in the new auditorium K.1.105</li>

</ul>
<p>We would like to recognise the principal moderators of our workshop, Annamari Erdei and Piotr Robouch, who gave up much of their personal time to ensure solid preparations and planning, including making provisions for how to share results more widely afterwards.</p><p>The migration to the latest version of our content management system for the website will bring improvements in content presentation and functionalities. The substantial work this entails is spear-headed by Paolo Bottoni and Carmen Lupea, keeping in mind the results of the websurvey about what visitors felt about our old site. The old site remains fully operational, but those who want to catch a glimpse can get a first impression at <a href="http://work.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/" title="http://work.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/" target="_blank">http://work.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/</a>. Only English and French versions have migrated for the most part and there is good reason why the site is called ‘<a href="http://work.mundusmaris.org/" target="_blank">work.mundusmaris.org</a>’ – very much still works in progress.</p><p>Because of the many activities in this period, we’re still working to reflect all this on the website (old and new). In a few days, you’ll see more of it there.</p><p>We received an offer by Martin Bohle to develop a blog on MM activities, which we gladly accepted. The modalities will be worked out in March 2012.</p><p>We interacted with the producer of a neat film clip about overfishing, who is being further developed and will shortly be available in several languages. This could be an excellent enrichment for the PacFish exhibition and other activities.</p><p>We gratefully acknowledge <b>some donations</b> to allow bringing African members and collaborators to Brussels for participation in activities in the period of Campus Plein Sud and <b>wonderful hospitality</b> to save on hotel costs and support our work in this practical way.</p><p>We have also completed preprations for our general assembly, scheduled for 3 March in the afternoon and followed by the projection of the film ‘Kayar – l’enfance prise aux filets’ by Thomas Grand at the Cercle des Voyagers in the centre of Brussels.</p><p>For more activities, see below.</p><p>---------------------------------------</p><p><b>Brussels</b></p><p>2012 is the year of gastronomy in Brussels under the motto: ‘Brusselicious’ with many activities, the biggest geared to strengthening the appeal of Brussels as an international tourist destination. We thought of contributing in a different manner:</p><p>Our “Brusselicious” project is now in the process of being build up with a representative group of partners: the Municipality of Koekelberg in Brussels (Including 4 schools), the Aquarium of Brussels, the Media centre (Atelier du Web) of the Municipality of Saint Gilles in Brussels, Oceana and MM. The project aims at raising awareness on “cooking and eating in a sustainable way” and combine that with highlighting the links with culture and inter-cultural dialogue. Several activities are planned: such as thematic, skills and capacity courses, participation in food related activities in Brussels and abroad to raise awareness and youth exchange activities around the sustainable theme with particular emphasis on seafood. Next step will be to apply to a Regional call for proposal of the Environment Agency in the Region of Brussels in order to secure funding and start work, if successful as soon as possible. Several people have volunteered to write contributions on food and culture that can also populate the website as resource material. Slow Food Brussels – Karikol - might also support/collaborate in the occasion of their annual ‘Goûter Bruxelles’ activities in September. Thomas Zadrozny holds the different lines of activities together and has been actively developing the contacts with partners in the municipalities and associations to shape up the project.</p><p>------------------------------</p><p><b>FAO – EAF Nansen Project</b></p><p>Aliou, in close collaboration with Gora Kane of UNI.V.ERE (a volunteer organisation for supporting environmental education in Senegal), has conducted a teacher training workshop in Hann, Senegal, the weekend of 17-18 February, to get the critical inputs of the teachers from the five schools participating in the pilot activities and prepare the live-tests in the schools to take place in the remainder of February through March 2012.</p><p>We have proposed to the FAO and the Nansen project (Kwame Koranteng) to use the following key ingredients as part of the teaching kits:</p>
<ul>

<li>the knowledge handbook on West African marine and coastal ecosystems of IUCN, prepared in the context of the Regional Programme on Environment Education, which is part of the efforts to strengthen environment education in the ordinary school curricula of Mauritania, Senegal, Gambia, Cape Verde, Guinea Bissau, Guinea and Sierra Leone;</li>

<li>the training manual prepared by Stay Green Foundation, IUCN’s local partner in Gambia and working also with MM in this context (manual to be used pending FAO approval)</li>

<li>a general approach, ideas sheet, several visual aids and monitoring and evaluation sheets developed under the current project and well as other support, incl. selected posters from the ‘Darwin series’, provided with our own resources to the joint effort: <a href="http://www.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/menu-exhibitions/bx1002/94-from-darwin-to-sustainable-seas?start=4" title="http://www.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/menu-exhibitions/bx1002/94-from-darwin-to-sustainable-seas?start=4" target="_blank">http://www.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/menu-exhibitions/bx1002/94-from-darwin-to-sustainable-seas?start=4</a></li>

</ul>
<p>All the materials have been delivered before for use in kick-off (training) workshop with teachers in participating schools as soon as clearance was obtained from FAO for deployment. A methodological and teaching aid book prepared by UNI.V.ERE, IUCN’s local partner in Senegal and working closely with MM in this context, supported the work with a teaching aid book produced already by them in the context of the regional PREE project.</p><p>Preparations also continued for a similar kick-off workshop in Gambia. The teachers have received advance copies of the IUCN knowledge handbook to familiarise themselves with the concepts and information materials about marine and coastal ecosystems in the region. Links to these publicly available resources and more information are provided: <a href="http://www.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/projects/2011-projects-en/162-faoen" title="http://www.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/projects/2011-projects-en/162-faoen" target="_blank">http://www.mundusmaris.org/index.php/en/projects/2011-projects-en/162-faoen</a>.</p><p>---------------------------------------</p><p><b>Nigeria / US</b></p><p>Stella continues with intensive networking and promotion of rebuilding and consolidating the basis for work in the Niger Delta. Provisions were made for spending time with people interested in working in and with MM in the Delta in March 2012.</p><p>--------------------------------------</p><p><b>India</b></p><p>We received an offer for volunteering from a student in her last year of studies at the Fisheries College and Research Institute, Tuticorin, Tamilnadu, India. This is courtesy also of our friend Nandeesha who spearheads efforts to introduce a gender course into the curriculum to account better for ground realities. We’re discussing modalities of cooperation.</p>
		</div>
		
	<!-- END BODY TEXT -->
		
			
		
	
	
			
				

